<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-706-768  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 706 768.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  July 4 1990 n1515 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Is there a future for the short-term view? (the Britishelectronics industry)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In a debate at the Interconnection Technology IndustrialConsortium's one-day conference, British market analysts evokedharsh criticism of the short term policies that are ruining theelectronics industry.andP;  Critics placed emphasis on the differencein financial structures between Japan, where banks are owners ofelectronics companies, and the United Kingdom, where banks do notplay that role.andP;  Further criticisms pointed to the Britishindustry's poor record in training, as contrasted with that ofJapan and Germany, as well as the industry's failure to sellsufficient British products on the overseas market.andP;  It was alsosuggested that pressure be exerted on the government to establishan industrial policy.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Industry AnalysisConferences and MeetingsMarket AnalysisJapanese CompetitionComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>